\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
How Much History Do Deep Sequence Models Need for AIS Trajectory Prediction?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Amitai Gal and Shalev Shiriki
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset
Technion — Faculty of Electrical and Computer Engineering
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset
Final Project Report — Deep Learning Course 046211 July 14, 2026
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This project studies vessel trajectory prediction from Automatic Identification
 System (AIS) data as a sequence learning problem.
 Given a history of position, speed, and direction sampled every 10 minutes,
 we predict latitude and longitude for the next 12 hours.
 The focus is how much temporal context a sequence model needs, and whether
 a more complex architecture uses long history more effectively.
 We compare kinematic extrapolation; fixed-context AR LSTMs with 9/12/18/24 h
 history; a Flat LSTM; a Transformer; a rolling short-window model; and an
 Adaptive Multi-Scale RNN that gates over several history lengths.
 Neural models reduce median FDE from 102.5 km to about 19–20 km.
 The best model is a 24 h Flat LSTM (18.80 km); the Transformer follows (19.40 km).
 In a controlled AR LSTM sweep, 
\begin_inset Formula $18\,\mathrm{h}$
\end_inset
 is best (19.71 km), while 24 h does not improve.
 Diagnostics show encoder states and gradients concentrate on recent history,
 so longer windows can add noise.
 The adaptive gate prefers 24 h only by a small soft margin; its four context
 states are nearly redundant, and forced uniform/fixed gates match learned performance.
 Long history matters, but useful adaptive history selection does not emerge
 from a simple gate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction and Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AIS broadcasts vessel position, speed over ground (SOG), course over ground
 (COG), heading, and time.
 These measurements form a temporal sequence, so trajectory prediction is
 a natural sequence-modeling task.
 We forecast a full 12-hour path: early errors can accumulate into large final
 displacements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The task combines RNN/LSTM memory, autoregressive (AR) decoding, Transformer
 self-attention, and training choices such as loss design, teacher forcing,
 and curriculum learning.
 The central question is: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset
how much history is useful for 12 h prediction?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset
 We test whether 24 h is always better than 18 or 12 h, whether a Transformer
 exploits long context better than an LSTM, and whether an adaptive gate can
 choose short vs.
 long history by itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prior work includes kinematic/statistical methods (dead reckoning, Kalman/EKF)
 [1]; RNN/seq2seq AIS predictors [2]; and attention/Transformer or geographic
 models such as TrAISformer and GeoTrackNet [3,4].
 Our contribution is a controlled history-length study with fixed data, horizon,
 and metrics, plus an analysis of whether adaptivity learns a real switching
 rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data and Window Construction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use public NOAA AIS merged into USA Combined.
 Trajectories are resampled to
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=10$
\end_inset
 min.
 Each example stores up to
\begin_inset Formula $T_h=144$
\end_inset
 history steps (24 h) and
\begin_inset Formula $T_f=72$
\end_inset
 future steps (12 h).
 Fixed-context runs use history suffixes of 54/72/108/144 steps (9/12/18/24 h).
 All models start from the same 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset
anchor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset
 (last observed position).
\end_layout

