\begin_layout Standard
Features include position, SOG, sine/cosine of COG and heading, deltas, and
 north/east velocity.
 Targets are anchor offsets
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation*}
y_t=P_t-P_0,\qquad \hat{P}_t=P_0+\hat{y}_t,
\end{equation*}

\end_inset
which reduce absolute-location dependence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data Filtering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A stationarity filter removes almost-static windows; a smart-motion filter
 removes abnormal loops; inland removal drops rivers/canals when most history
 points are not near open water.
 After filtering, 363,014/535,967 windows remain (67.7%).
 Train/validation/test splits are by trajectory ID (255,133 / 34,549 / 73,332)
 to avoid voyage leakage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Metrics and Motion Buckets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We measure geodesic error with Haversine distance (km).
\textbf{ FDE}
 is the error after 12 h;
\textbf{ ADE}
 averages error over all 72 future steps.
 Ranking uses
\textbf{ median FDE}
 because long-horizon errors are heavy-tailed.
 For analysis only (not training), windows are labeled 
\emph{straight}
 vs.
\emph{ maneuver}
 from history features such as straightness
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\mathrm{direct}}/L_{\mathrm{path}}$
\end_inset
 and COG variability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Models and Training
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\textbf{Kinematic baseline.}
 Extrapolate the last SOG and COG for 12 h.
\textbf{ Fixed-context AR LSTM.}
 Encoder–decoder LSTM (hidden 256, 2 layers, dropout 0.2); free-running at
 test time; same architecture for 9/12/18/24 h.
\textbf{ Flat LSTM.}
 Predicts all 72 offsets at once (no AR feedback).
\textbf{ Transformer.}
 Encoder-only:
\begin_inset Formula $d=128$
\end_inset
, 8 heads, 4 layers, FFN 512.
\textbf{ Sliding 3 h×4.}
 Short predictor rolled four times.
\textbf{ Adaptive Multi-Scale AR.}
 Shared LSTM encodes nested 9/12/18/24 h suffixes; MLP gate produces
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\mathrm{softmax}(\cdot)$
\end_inset
; context is
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_k\alpha_k h_k$
\end_inset
.
\end_layout

