\begin_layout Subsection
AR History Sweep — Why 18 h Beats 24 h
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename data/results/USA Combined/unknown/exp_coastal/report_figures/fig_ar_context_sweep.png
	width 62text%
\end_inset

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
AR LSTM history sweep: median FDE improves to 18 h then worsens at 24 h.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With architecture fixed, median FDE is non-monotonic: 20.43 → 19.99 → 
\textbf{19.71}
 → 20.30 km for 9/12/18/24 h.
 Diagnostics on shared windows explain why more history is not better:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\textbf{Occlusion:}
 zeroing the newest 3 h raises mean FDE by ~6–9 km; zeroing the oldest 3 h
 changes it by ≲0.7 km, and for AR 24 h slightly 
\emph{helps}
 (−0.09 km).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\textbf{Gradients:}
 AR 24 h places 52.6% of
\begin_inset Formula $|\partial L/\partial x_t|$
\end_inset
 mass on the newest 3 h and only 1.8% on the oldest 3 h.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\textbf{Hidden state:}
 ≥95% cosine match to the full-history encoder state needs only ~11–13 h of
 recent context even in the 24 h model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\textbf{Weights:}
 AR 24 h has the most negative LSTM forget bias (layer 0), i.e., a stronger
 tendency to discard early memory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the encoder bottleneck largely saturates near ~12 h; the extra 6 h in
 a 24 h window is weakly used and can add noise.
\end_layout

