\begin_layout Section
Discussion, Limitations, and Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename data/results/USA Combined/unknown/exp_coastal/report_figures/fig_error_vs_horizon.png
	width 58text%
\end_inset

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Error grows with forecast hour; long-horizon prediction is harder than nearby
 steps.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) Neural nets learn dynamics beyond last-state kinematics.
 (2) More history is not always better under a fixed LSTM bottleneck.
 (3) Direct prediction can beat AR by avoiding accumulation.
 (4) Adaptivity needs stronger inductive bias than soft pooling of redundant
 nested encodings (separate experts, step-dependent gates, or explicit motion
 features).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Limitations: coarse land mask; USA coastal data only; no full per-model hyperparameter
 sweep.
 Future work: land-penalty ablation, Transformer history sweep, geographic features,
 and gates conditioned on straightness/COG variance or future time index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
12 h AIS forecasting is hard, but deep models improve dramatically over kinematics.
 Best overall: Flat LSTM 24 h (18.80 km).
 Best AR history length: 18 h — not 24 h — because useful context saturates
 and older hours contribute little.
 A simple multi-scale gate collapses to a soft 24 h prior without learning motion-aware
 switching.
 Temporal context matters; learning 
\emph{how much}
 history to use requires more than a shallow gate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Ethics Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\textbf{Students:}
 Amitai Gal, Shalev Shiriki.
\textbf{ Title:}
 How Much History Do Deep Sequence Models Need for AIS Trajectory Prediction?
 This academic project compares sequence models on public AIS data.
 Predictions are approximate and
\textbf{ not}
 for navigation, safety, or enforcement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\textbf{LLM stakeholder analysis.}
 We used ChatGPT to draft stakeholder answers.
 Stakeholders: (i) coastal/maritime-safety authorities; (ii) shipping companies
 and ports; (iii) vessel crews/operators.
 Authorities and industry may misuse uncertain forecasts; crews may be affected
 if research outputs are treated as navigation aids; movement data also raises
 privacy/surveillance concerns.
 Explanations must call the system a statistical research tool, report error
 metrics/limits/failure cases, and state that it does not replace human navigation,
 radar, or certified procedures.
 Responsibility lies with developers and any deploying organization; in this
 course project we must report limits and failure modes honestly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\textbf{Reflection.}
 Good average FDE does not imply safe individual cases.
 Ethical communication must include uncertainty, geographic limits, failure
 examples, privacy risks, and a clear ban on replacing certified maritime systems.
\end_layout

